 2 Simulated Annealing and the Sudoku Solver 2.1 Introduction Why Simulated Annealing?: the goal programming in Patchworks is based on Simulated Annealing Simulated annealing is a stochastic optimization algorithm inspired by the physical process of annealing in metallurgy, where a material is heated and then slowly cooled to reduce defects and reach a stable, low-energy state. The algorithm searches for an optimal solution by repeatedly generating small random changes to the current solution and evaluating whether they improve an objective function. Better solutions are always accepted, while worse solutions may also be accepted with a probability that depends on the increase in the objective function and the current temperature (the control parameter that determines how willing the algorithm is to accept solutions that are worse than the current solution). This probabilistic acceptance allows the algorithm to escape local optima (A local optimum is a solution that is better than all nearby alternatives but is not necessarily the best solution among all possible solutions in the entire search space) and explore a wider region of the search space during the early stages of the optimization. As the temperature gradually decreases according to a cooling schedule(the predefined rule that determines how the temperature is gradually reduced during simulated annealing, controlling the transition from broad exploration of the search space to focused refinement of promising solutions), the likelihood of accepting worse solutions diminishes, causing the search to become increasingly focused on refining the best solutions found. This balance between exploration and exploitation makes simulated annealing an effective technique for solving complex optimization problems with many local optima (like in a forest estate model). A good explainer is found here 2.2 Simple Model The following simple simulated annealing model begins by defining an objective function, f(x) = x^2 + 10(x), which the algorithm attempts to minimize. A random starting value of (x) is selected within a specified range, and its corresponding objective function value is calculated. During each iteration, a candidate solution is generated by adding a small random deviation to the current value of (x). The candidate is then evaluated using the objective function and compared with the current solution. If the candidate produces a lower objective function value, it is always accepted. If it is worse, it may still be accepted with a probability determined by the Metropolis acceptance criterion, (P = e^{-Delta/T}), where (Delta) is the increase in the objective function and (T) is the current temperature. This probabilistic acceptance of inferior solutions allows the algorithm to escape local minima and continue exploring the search. As the optimization progresses, the temperature is gradually reduced using a cooling schedule, causing the algorithm to become increasingly selective (read “greedy”) about accepting worse solutions. Early in the search, the high temperature encourages exploration by allowing occasional uphill moves, whereas later iterations behave more like a greedy optimization algorithm, accepting primarily improving solutions. Throughout the optimization, the algorithm records the current solution, objective function value, temperature, and whether each proposed move was accepted. These data are then used to visualize the optimization process, including the change in objective function over time, the trajectory of the search variable, and the path taken across the objective function landscape. Although this example optimizes a single variable, it illustrates the same principles used in more complex applications, such as Sudoku solving below, where the search space consists of many decision variables and the objective is to minimize the number of constraint violations. #------------------------------------------------------- # Simulated Annealing Example # Objective: Minimize f(x) = x^2 + 10*sin(x) #------------------------------------------------------- # Objective function objective &lt;- function(x) { x^2 + 10 * sin(x) } #----------------------------- # Initialize algorithm #----------------------------- current_x &lt;- runif(1, -10, 10) current_cost &lt;- objective(current_x) temperature &lt;- 10 cooling_rate &lt;- 0.99 iterations &lt;- 1000 # Store results results &lt;- tibble( iteration = 1, x = current_x, cost = current_cost, temperature = temperature, accepted = TRUE ) #----------------------------- # Simulated Annealing #----------------------------- for (i in 2:iterations) { # Generate a nearby candidate solution candidate_x &lt;- current_x + rnorm(1, mean = 0, sd = 1) candidate_cost &lt;- objective(candidate_x) # Difference in objective value delta &lt;- candidate_cost - current_cost accept &lt;- FALSE # Accept better solutions if (delta &lt;= 0) { accept &lt;- TRUE } else { # Accept worse solutions with probability probability &lt;- exp(-delta / temperature) if (runif(1) &lt; probability) { accept &lt;- TRUE } } # Update current solution if accepted if (accept) { current_x &lt;- candidate_x current_cost &lt;- candidate_cost } # Reduce temperature temperature &lt;- temperature * cooling_rate # Save iteration results &lt;- add_row( results, iteration = i, x = current_x, cost = current_cost, temperature = temperature, accepted = accept ) } #----------------------------- # Best solution found #----------------------------- best &lt;- results %&gt;% filter(cost == min(cost)) print(best) ## # A tibble: 4 × 5 ## iteration x cost temperature accepted ## &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;lgl&gt; ## 1 65 -1.31 -7.95 5.26 TRUE ## 2 66 -1.31 -7.95 5.20 FALSE ## 3 67 -1.31 -7.95 5.15 FALSE ## 4 68 -1.31 -7.95 5.10 FALSE 2.2.1 Plot objective value The objective value plot depicts how the value of the function being minimized changes over the course of the simulated annealing process. The horizontal axis represents iteration number, while the vertical axis shows the current objective (or cost) value at each step. Each point reflects the quality of the solution at that iteration, allowing the progression of the algorithm to be tracked numerically over time. Early in the search, the objective value typically fluctuates as the algorithm explores the solution space and occasionally accepts worse solutions. As the temperature decreases, the objective values generally trend downward and stabilize, indicating that the algorithm is converging toward a low-cost (near-optimal) solution. #----------------------------- ggplot(results, aes(iteration, cost)) + geom_line() + labs( title = &quot;Simulated Annealing&quot;, subtitle = &quot;Objective Function Over Time&quot;, x = &quot;Iteration&quot;, y = &quot;Objective Function&quot; ) + theme_bw() 2.2.2 Plot search trajectory The search trajectory plot depicts how the value of the decision variable ((x)) changes over successive iterations of the simulated annealing algorithm. The horizontal axis represents the iteration number, while the vertical axis shows the current value of (x) at each accepted step in the optimization. Rather than illustrating the quality of the solution directly, the plot shows how the algorithm navigates the search space over time. During the early iterations, larger fluctuations in (x) are typically observed as the high temperature encourages exploration by allowing occasional acceptance of worse solutions. As the temperature decreases, these fluctuations become smaller and the trajectory begins to stabilize, indicating that the algorithm is transitioning from broad exploration to local refinement. Ultimately, the plot demonstrates the convergence behavior of simulated annealing as it progressively settles near the value of (x) that minimizes the objective function. #----------------------------- ggplot(results, aes(iteration, x)) + geom_line() + labs( title = &quot;Search Trajectory&quot;, x = &quot;Iteration&quot;, y = &quot;x&quot; ) + theme_bw() 2.2.3 Plot objective function with optimization path The optimization path chart depicts the sequence of solutions explored by the simulated annealing algorithm as it searches for the minimum of the objective function. The solid curve represents the objective function, (f(x)=x^2+10(x)), while each red point corresponds to a solution accepted by the algorithm during an iteration. The horizontal position of a point indicates the value of the decision variable (x), and the vertical position representsthe corresponding objective function value. Reading the points in chronological order reveals the trajectory taken throughthe search space, illustrating how the algorithm moves between candidate solutions rather than progressing directly toward the optimum. The distribution of points demonstrates the balance between exploration and exploitation that characterizes simulated annealing. During the early stages of the optimization, the point may appear widely scattered, reflecting the high temperature that allows the algorithm to accept occasional worse solutions and explore different regions of the objective function. As the temperature decreases, the accepted points become increasingly concentrated around the global minimum, indicating that the algorithm is becoming more selective and focusing on refining the best solution found. The chart therefore provides a visual representation of how simulated annealing initially performs a broad search of the solution landscape before gradually converging toward an optimal solution. #----------------------------- curve_data &lt;- tibble( x = seq(-10, 10, length.out = 500) ) %&gt;% mutate(cost = objective(x)) ggplot(curve_data, aes(x, cost)) + geom_line() + geom_point( data = results, aes(x = x, y = cost), colour = &quot;red&quot;, alpha = 0.4 ) + labs( title = &quot;Optimization Path&quot;, x = &quot;x&quot;, y = &quot;Objective Function&quot; ) + theme_bw() 2.3 Sudoku Solver Who doesn’t like Sudoku….but sometime you have to guess and/or cheat. The following is based on a python algorithm depicted here. The Sudoku solver is a R based simulated annealing algorithm that treats the puzzle as an optimization problem rather than solving it through exhaustive search. It begins with a partially filled 9×9 grid where zeros represent empty cells, and it identifies which values are fixed and which can be changed. The solver then constructs an initial candidate solution by randomly filling each 3×3 block so that every block contains the numbers 1 through 9 exactly once. This guarantees that block constraints are always satisfied, leaving only row and column violations to be corrected (see constraint decomposition definition at the bottom). It evaluates the quality of a solution using a cost (error) function that counts duplicate values in rows and columns, with the goal of driving this error down to zero. To improve the grid, the solver uses simulated annealing, a probabilistic optimization technique inspired by physical cooling processes.At each step, it generates a new candidate solution by swapping two non-fixed values within a randomly chosen block, preserving block validity while altering row and column structure. If the swap reduces the number of conflicts, it is accepted; if it increases the error, it may still be accepted with a probability that depends on the current “temperature” parameter. This temperature gradually decreases over time, allowing broad exploration early on and more focused, “greedy” improvements later. Through repeated iterations of proposing, evaluating, and conditionally accepting changes, the solver progressively reduces conflicts until it reaches a valid Sudoku solution or stops after a set number of iterations. The seed for the Sudoku solver has been set to 999 to yield a solved Sudoku Solution…not all randomized Sudoku boards can be solved within the set iteration limit. To experiment with various Sudoku boards set the seed to NULL: set.seed(999) in the code chunk below. 2.3.1 Code Notes: 2.3.1.1 INITIAL SUDOKU SETUP The generateFullSudoku function creates a complete, valid Sudoku grid by first building a structured base pattern and then randomizing it by shuffling rows, columns, and the numbers 1–9 while preserving all Sudoku rules. The createPuzzle function takes this full solution and randomly replaces a specified fraction of cells with zeros, creating a partially filled puzzle. Finally, generateSudokuWithZeros combines these steps to produce a new Sudoku puzzle with empty cells each time it is run. 2.3.1.2 Initial Sigma The estimateInitialSigma function estimates a suitable starting “temperature” for simulated annealing by sampling how much the Sudoku error changes under random moves. It repeatedly performs random swaps within blocks, records the resulting error values, and collects these into a sample set. Finally, it returns the standard deviation of those errors, which serves as a data-driven measure of how large typical changes are and helps scale the initial acceptance probability appropriately. 2.3.1.3 DEFINE 3x3 BLOCKS The getBlocks function constructs and returns a list of all nine 3×3 subgrids (blocks) in the Sudoku by generating the row–column coordinate pairs for each block. Each element of the list represents one block and contains the indices of the cells belonging to that block, making it easy to access and manipulate them. This is important because the solver relies on operating within these blocks—such as swapping values—while preserving block validity, which simplifies the problem by ensuring that only row and column conflicts need to be optimized. 2.3.1.4 GENERATE A NEIGHBOR (STATE TRANSITION) The swapCells function repeatedly selects two random cells within a given 3×3 block and swaps their values, but only if both cells are not fixed (i.e., not part of the original puzzle). This ensures that the original clues remain unchanged while still allowing the solver to modify the grid. It is important because it generates new candidate solutions for the simulated annealing process while preserving block validity. # Set-Up set.seed(999) generateFullSudoku &lt;- function() { base &lt;- matrix(0, 9, 9) # Simple valid base pattern for (i in 1:9) { for (j in 1:9) { base[i,j] &lt;- ((i-1)*3 + floor((i-1)/3) + j - 1) %% 9 + 1 } } # Randomly shuffle rows within blocks for (b in 0:2) { rows &lt;- sample(1:3) + b*3 base[(b*3+1):(b*3+3), ] &lt;- base[rows, ] } # Randomly shuffle columns within blocks for (b in 0:2) { cols &lt;- sample(1:3) + b*3 base[, (b*3+1):(b*3+3)] &lt;- base[, cols] } # Shuffle numbers 1–9 globally perm &lt;- sample(1:9) base &lt;- matrix(perm[base], 9, 9) return(base) } createPuzzle &lt;- function(fullSudoku, emptyFraction = 0.6) { puzzle &lt;- fullSudoku # Total cells to remove n_remove &lt;- round(81 * emptyFraction) # Random positions positions &lt;- sample(1:81, n_remove) puzzle[positions] &lt;- 0 return(puzzle) } generateSudokuWithZeros &lt;- function(emptyFraction = 0.6) { full &lt;- generateFullSudoku() puzzle &lt;- createPuzzle(full, emptyFraction) return(puzzle) } # ========================================================== # PRINT FUNCTION (for visualization only) # ========================================================== printSudoku &lt;- function(sudoku) { for (i in 1:9) { # Print horizontal divider between 3x3 blocks if (i %% 3 == 1 &amp;&amp; i != 1) cat(&quot;---------------------
&quot;) line &lt;- &quot;&quot; for (j in 1:9) { # Print vertical divider if (j %% 3 == 1 &amp;&amp; j != 1) line &lt;- paste0(line, &quot;| &quot;) line &lt;- paste0(line, sudoku[i,j], &quot; &quot;) } cat(line, &quot;
